{"id":"1210.1318","submitter":"Xiaodong Luo","authors":"Xiaodong Luo and Ibrahim Hoteit","title":"Ensemble Kalman filtering with residual nudging","comments":"Published paper in Tellus A, open access via the\n  http://www.tellusa.net/index.php/tellusa/article/view/17130","journal-ref":"Tellus A 2012, 64, 17130","doi":"10.3402/tellusa.v64i0.17130","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.ao-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Covariance inflation and localization are two important techniques that are\nused to improve the performance of the ensemble Kalman filter (EnKF) by (in\neffect) adjusting the sample covariances of the estimates in the state space.\nIn this work an additional auxiliary technique, called residual nudging, is\nproposed to monitor and, if necessary, adjust the residual norms of state\nestimates in the observation space. In an EnKF with residual nudging, if the\nresidual norm of an analysis is larger than a pre-specified value, then the\nanalysis is replaced by a new one whose residual norm is no larger than a\npre-specified value. Otherwise the analysis is considered as a reasonable\nestimate and no change is made. A rule for choosing the pre-specified value is\nsuggested. Based on this rule, the corresponding new state estimates are\nexplicitly derived in case of linear observations. Numerical experiments in the\n40-dimensional Lorenz 96 model show that introducing residual nudging to an\nEnKF may improve its accuracy and/or enhance its stability against filter\ndivergence, especially in the small ensemble scenario.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 4 Oct 2012 07:23:46 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-10-05"}
